<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What do blood pressure numbers mean?", answer: "Blood pressure is measured with two numbers: systolic (top number) and diastolic (bottom number), expressed in millimeters of mercury (mmHg). Systolic pressure measures the force when your heart beats and pushes blood through the arteries. Diastolic pressure measures the force when your heart rests between beats. A reading of 120/80 mmHg means a systolic pressure of 120 and a diastolic pressure of 80." },
  { question: "What is a normal blood pressure reading?", answer: "According to the American Heart Association, normal blood pressure is a systolic reading below 120 mmHg AND a diastolic reading below 80 mmHg. Elevated blood pressure is systolic 120-129 with diastolic below 80. Stage 1 hypertension is systolic 130-139 OR diastolic 80-89. Stage 2 hypertension is systolic 140 or higher OR diastolic 90 or higher. A hypertensive crisis requires systolic above 180 and/or diastolic above 120." },
  { question: "What is pulse pressure and why does it matter?", answer: "Pulse pressure is the difference between systolic and diastolic blood pressure. A normal pulse pressure is between 40 and 60 mmHg. A wide pulse pressure (above 60) can indicate stiff arteries, heart valve problems, or hyperthyroidism. A narrow pulse pressure (below 40) may suggest heart failure or significant blood loss. Pulse pressure tends to increase with age as arteries become less elastic." },
  { question: "What is mean arterial pressure (MAP)?", answer: "Mean arterial pressure (MAP) is the average pressure in your arteries during one cardiac cycle. It is calculated as diastolic pressure plus one-third of the pulse pressure: MAP = DBP + 1/3(SBP - DBP). A normal MAP is between 70 and 100 mmHg. MAP is important because it represents the actual driving pressure for blood flow to organs. A MAP below 60 mmHg may not provide adequate blood flow to vital organs." },
  { question: "How often should I check my blood pressure?", answer: "The American Heart Association recommends that adults with normal blood pressure have it checked at least once a year during a regular health visit. If your readings are elevated or high, more frequent monitoring is needed — ideally at home with a validated blood pressure monitor. For home monitoring, take readings at the same time each day, sit quietly for 5 minutes beforehand, and average 2-3 readings taken one minute apart." }
]) %>

